review_blob: This is my go-to beer. A little less common than SNs Pale Ale, but not rare. Pours a dark brown, almost black, with a tan head. Taste is mostly chocolate, with a very smooth finish.

12 oz bottle. Pours yellow with a white head that lasts. This is a bad beer. This is a very bad beer. When I poured this into a glass, my friend commented that it looked like Corona; it didnt get any better from there.
beer_name: Southern Tier PMX (Phin & Matts Extraordinary Ale)

review_blob: 12 oz bottle. Pours dark brown with a small head. This one surprised me; Anheuser Busch managed to make a good beer. It tastes like a real porter, if a bit bland. All the elements are there: roasted malts, smoothness, chocolatey finish. A great beer for the price.

22 oz bottle. Pours pitch black, with a small, lasting head. "Wow" is the only word that sums up this stout. Prevalent bitter chocolate taste, but very smooth. Wow, this stout is delicious. In fact, Im going to drink another one.

12 oz bottle. Pours a dark brown, almost black with minimal head. A good porter, a little too much hops for my taste, but still good. The name is a bit of a misnomer, though; I really cant taste any oatmeal in it.

12 oz bottle. Pours dark brown/black, with a small, tan head. Very interesting porter, in my opinion. The entry and body have plenty of hoppy bitterness, but then it levels out to a smooth, traditional porter taste. My main problem with this beer is that its a seasonal.

12 oz bottle. Pours black, with little to no head. An interesting beer that mostly works. For this beer they added lactose to sweeten up the stout. Yes, lactose, as in, that stuff that gives you muscle cramps. This mostly works, but at times it seems as though the taste of the milk and the taste of the stout are at odds with each other, so the flavor can be a bit schizophrenic at times. Overall fairly good, but I think I might like their plain porter better.

12 oz bottle. Pours pitch black with a small, tan, long-lasting head. A great example of a stout; this is the beer that got me into beer. The flavor of the roasted malts is apparent, but smooth. A bit of hoppy bitterness is there, but mixed in with the malts. An excellent beer.

12 oz bottle. Pours a dark, reddish brown with a minimal, off-white head. Tastes halfway between a red ale and a brown ale, however, there is an apparent corn taste that really keeps this from being a good beer. I knew I should have gone with Troegs.

YARGH! Me hearties! This brew be smoother than the voice of a bar-wench after a long voyage, Blacker than a night on the Cape of Good Hope, and tastier than fresh gold dubloons! And at 8% alcohol, itll have ye dancin on the plank in no time! YARGH!

12 oz bottle. Pours, well, pours like Guinness. Mouth-feel was pretty thin for a stout. The taste was watery, with only a slight bitterness at the end. Tasted like a watered-down Sierra Nevada Stout. I think this might be due to the nitrogen capsule in the bottle, because on tap this is delicious. Or maybe, I just got a bad batch. So given the choice, avoid the bottle, go for the tap.

12 oz bottle. Pours dark brown with a thin, tan head that dissipates quickly. Overall the taste is good, and what one would expect from a porter, if a bit bland. There is an obvious taste of corn, however. But it lives up to how I feel about Yuengling: a good beer at a good price.

12 oz bottle. Pours pitch black with a dark tan head, minimal lacing. Delicious. Substantial roasted malt flavor, but still smooth. Very Delicious. Excellent finish that leaves you wanting more. Oh, and did i say it was delicious? Because it is.
18 oz Bottle. Pours dark brown, almost black with a tan head. Sweet taste. Oatmeal flavor is very apparent, but not overpowering. I will definitely buy this again.

I really wanted to like this beer. I mean, its from Virginia! But I just couldnt. Nice entry, nice finish, but the problem is the body. To me it just tasted burnt. Not enjoyable at all, in my opinion.
